Is there a relationship between global self esteem and BMI?

Madeleine Guettler

5/7/2021

Load Data

original_eating_disorder <- read_csv("Body_Perception_Consent_Form_Sheet.csv")
eating_disorder_variable_description <- read_csv("Body_Perception_Data_Dictionary.csv")
meter_conversion = c(original_eating_disorder$height_measured / 100)
meter_squared = c(meter_conversion^2)
original_eating_disorder$bmi =  c(original_eating_disorder$weight_measured / meter_squared)
eating_disorder <- original_eating_disorder %>%
  select(id_number, case, vassize, vassatis, bmi, rsestotal) %>%
  na.omit()

There are no missing values.

Introduction

Currently approximately 3.4 million people struggle with eating disorders in the UK.Unfortunately, eating disorders have the highest mortality rate out of all psychiatric illnesses.This study is important because it looks at how the eating disorder and non eating disorder individuals see themselves and looks at how global self esteem is affected by the way we perceive our bodies and where were at weight wise. I think this is important to study as what if eating disorder individuals could calculate a healthy place they can be at with their weight where they wont struggle so much with negative body image and self esteem as this really connects directly to our self worth which then in turn can make the eating disorder stronger or less strong.

This data set takes thirty women with eating disorders and thirty without eating disorders in the UK and tests for differences in the way they perceive themselves and others in addition to their satisfaction with their sizes. The data set was found on the website: https://data.bris.ac.uk/data/dataset/10pmme2kf4swp2rk58d9vuhwve

My research questions was, how does ones perception of body size, amount of body satisfaction effect your amount of self esteem? And does the lower your bmi gets actually make you have less self esteem?

Each case in this dataset is one of 60 people, and includes people who either have an eating disorder or do not an eating disorder and the variables aim to describe certain aspects of eachs individuals bmi value,body image, body satisfaction/view of one selfs body, and self esteem.

The main variable of interest is rsestotal. There are no units in this measurement. It simply measures global self-esteem by measuring both positive and negative feelings about the self that ranges from 0-30.

My numerical explanatory variable is actually a variable that I created in my code above, where I took the original variables height_measured which had the variable and weight_measured in the dataset to figure out each of the cases BMIs. This new variable that I created has a unit of measurement of kg/m^2.

My categorical explanatory variable is:

  1. case: Whether participant has an eating disorder or not
    1. 1 = yes
    2. 0 = no

Statistical Inference

3.1 Methods

The components of our multiple linear regression model are the following:

  • Outcome variable y = Global Self Esteem (no unit of measure)
  • Numerical explanatory variable x1 = BMI (in kg/m^2)
  • Categorical explanatory variable x2 = Case (0 = No Eating Disorder, 1 = Eating Disorder)

3.2 Model Results

Table 2. Regression table of linear model of global self esteem as a function of bmi and diagnosis case.

eating_disorder_model = lm(rsestotal ~ bmi + case, data = eating_disorder)
get_regression_table(eating_disorder_model)
## # A tibble: 3  7
##   term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept   23.9       5.21      4.59    0       13.5     34.3  
## 2 bmi         -0.113     0.222    -0.512   0.611   -0.558    0.331
## 3 case: 1     -9.12      1.66     -5.51    0      -12.4     -5.80

3.3 Interpreting the regression table

We can interpret the estimated coefficients in the linear model as follows:

  • The intercept 23.878 represents the average global self esteem for non-eating disorder individuals with a bmi of 0. This does not make sense in context, because its not possible for anyone to have a bmi of 0.

  • The estimate for the slope for bmi -0.113 is the associated change in the average global self esteem depending on an individuals bmi, for a case. Based on this estimate, for a fixed case, for every 1 kg/m^2 increase in bmi, there was an associated decrease in global self esteem by 0.0113, on average.

  • The estimates for the coefficient case1 is the offset in the intercept relative to the reference case,individuals with no eating_disorder (for a fixed bmi). In other words, for a fixed bmi, the average global self esteem is 9.117 lower relative to non-eating disorder individuals.

3.4 Inference for multiple regression

Using the output of our regression table well test the null hypothesis for our numerical explanatory variable. The null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between global self esteem and bmi (the population slope is zero).

  • H_0: beta_bmi = 0; H_A: beta_bmi 0

There appears to be a negative relationship between the bmi and global self esteem after controlling for case, (slope of -0.113). Furthermore, it seems to be a not very meaningful relationship since in Table 2 we see

  • the 95% confidence interval for the population slope is (-0.558, 0.331), which is both on the negative and positive side.
  • the p-value > 0.05 is rather big, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the population slope is zero in favor of the alternative.

So taking into account potential sampling variation in results (for example a different group of people in general) the relationship between bmi and global self esteem overall is negative based off the slope, after controlling for case.

We can also see that the coefficient for the case level is statistically significant and include confidence intervals entirely on the negative side, which means that, after controlling for bmi, the eating disorder individuals have average global self esteem scores that are significantly different from those of non eating disorder individuals (i.e., the coefficient is significantly different from zero).

3.5 Residual Analysis

We conducted a residual analysis to see if there was any systematic pattern of residuals for the statistical model we ran. Because if there are systematic patterns, then we cannot fully trust our confidence intervals and p-values above.

Our residual analysis consisted of (1) a residual histogram to check for normality of the residuals, (2) a scatterplot of residuals against the fitted (predicted) values, (3) a scatterplot of the residuals against bmi, and (4) side-by-side boxplots of the residuals for each case (eating disorder/non-eating disorder group).

residual_table = get_regression_points(eating_disorder_model)

gf_histogram( ~ residual, color = "white", fill = "steelblue", data = residual_table) + 
  labs(x = "Residuals", y = "Frequency") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 5. Histogram of residuals for the linear model 

gf_point(residual ~ rsestotal_hat, data = residual_table) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 6. Scatterplot of Residuals against the fitted values 

gf_point(residual ~ bmi, data = residual_table) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "BMI (in kg/m^2)", y = "Residuals") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 7. Scatterplot of Residuals against bmi 

gf_boxplot(residual ~ case, data = residual_table) + 
  labs(x = "Case", y = "Residuals") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 8. Boxplot of residuals for each case (0 = non-eating disorder individuals, 1 = eatig disorder individuals

In Figure 5 the histogram is nearly normal where there are some dips, but the shape is closer to a bell curve versus a skewed distribution.

In Figure 6 for the scatterplot of residuals against fitted values, the variability is not consistent where for the fitted values of around 11-13.5 the residuals are much more then the residuals around the fitted values of around 20 onwards.

This corresponds to Figure 7, where there is a high degree of variability. There seems to be a lower variability in residuals up till about a bmi of 17; then between bmis 17 and 25 there is significantly more variance in residuals and finally, at a bmi of 25 and over there seems to be an decrease in variability again.

In Figure 8 the boxplots of the two cases are different. The non eating disorder boxplot is almost symmetrical, but not quite where it is slightly right skewed. While the eating disorder boxplot is extremely right skewed.

If we return to Figure 4, the colored scatterplot, we can see that both the reference level group of eating disorder individuals does not have a very strong linear relationships and the linear relationship for eating disorder individuals is even weaker.

Overall this dataset does not meet the conditions of a regression model, so the findings of this regression analysis should be interpreted with caution.

Conclusions

Overall we found that there is not much association between global self esteem and bmi in eating disorder and non eating disorder individuals. After controlling for cases there seemed to be a decrease in global self esteem of 0.113 for every 1 kg/m^2 increase in bmi.

Overall while the finding suggests that there is generally a downward trend in global self esteem as bmi increases, these findings are not necessarily accurate due to after running a residual analysis, we found several pieces of evidence that the conditions for a regression model were not met, where the residuals histogram of this data set was not near normal, and there was significant variance in the residual scatterplots.

In general I was slightly disappointed in the fact that there wasnt much correlation between global self esteem and bmi as somehow I thought that there could be this sort of sweet spot where all the sudden an individual had better global self esteem, but I do think it would be important to see if any of the other variables in the original dataset had any clear correlation with global self esteem.
